<paragraph id="104736CCFFB4FFF6FF642EC3FF30FC25" blockId="2.[151,1436,703,1016]" pageId="2" pageNumber="303">
<emphasis id="228CEADEFFB4FFF6FF642EC3FE40FD20" bold="true" box="[199,431,740,765]" pageId="2" pageNumber="303">Genus distribution.</emphasis>
<collectingRegion id="D23CF82EFFB4FFF6FE152EC2FDFEFD21" box="[438,529,741,764]" country="Solomon Islands" name="Western" pageId="2" pageNumber="303">Western</collectingRegion>
Pacific (from 
<collectingCountry id="68EF765CFFB4FFF6FD162EC2FD1AFD21" box="[693,757,741,764]" name="Japan" pageId="2" pageNumber="303">Japan</collectingCountry>
to 
<collectingCountry id="68EF765CFFB4FFF6FCBA2EC2FC5CFD20" box="[793,947,740,765]" name="New Zealand" pageId="2" pageNumber="303">New Zealand</collectingCountry>
, including 
<collectingCountry id="68EF765CFFB4FFF6FB932EC3FB6AFD20" box="[1072,1157,740,765]" name="Taiwan" pageId="2" pageNumber="303">Taiwan</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry id="68EF765CFFB4FFF6FB332EC3FB1DFD20" box="[1168,1266,740,765]" name="Vietnam" pageId="2" pageNumber="303">Vietnam</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry id="68EF765CFFB4FFF6FB5E2EC2FAB3FD21" box="[1277,1372,741,764]" name="Vanuatu" pageId="2" pageNumber="303">Vanuatu</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry id="68EF765CFFB4FFF6FAC42EC2FEE3FCFD" name="New Caledonia" pageId="2" pageNumber="303">New Caledonia</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry id="68EF765CFFB4FFF6FEB42F20FED1FCFD" box="[279,318,775,800]" name="Fiji" pageId="2" pageNumber="303">Fiji</collectingCountry>
and 
<collectingCountry id="68EF765CFFB4FFF6FED52F20FDD9FCFD" box="[374,566,775,800]" name="Solomon Islands" pageId="2" pageNumber="303">Solomon Islands</collectingCountry>
), eastern Pacific (from 
<collectingRegion id="D23CF82EFFB4FFF6FC9D2F20FC5FFCFD" box="[830,944,775,800]" country="United States of America" name="California" pageId="2" pageNumber="303">California</collectingRegion>
to Gulf of 
<collectingCountry id="68EF765CFFB4FFF6FB8D2F2FFB66FCFD" box="[1070,1161,776,800]" name="Panama" pageId="2" pageNumber="303">
<collectingRegion id="D23CF82EFFB4FFF6FB8D2F2FFB66FCFD" box="[1070,1161,776,800]" country="Panama" name="Panama" pageId="2" pageNumber="303">Panama</collectingRegion>
</collectingCountry>
) and the Caribbean Sea, 
<quantity id="D7009B29FFB4FFF6FF342F0BFEC8FC99" box="[151,295,812,837]" metricMagnitude="3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.6275" metricValueMax="6.779999999999999" metricValueMin="0.475" pageId="2" pageNumber="303" unit="m" value="3627.5" valueMax="6780.0" valueMin="475.0">475–6780 m</quantity>
. Early Oligocene–Recent. A chiton head valve was found in the early Oligocene deep-sea deposits at a wood-fall in 
<collectingRegion id="D23CF82EFFB4FFF6FE9F2F68FE2EFCB5" box="[316,449,847,872]" country="United States of America" name="Washington" pageId="2" pageNumber="303">Washington</collectingRegion>
State (
<bibRefCitation id="74694B3DFFB4FFF6FDAC2F68FCEBFCB5" author="Kiel" box="[527,772,847,872]" pageId="2" pageNumber="303" refId="ref15350" refString="Kiel, S. &amp; Goedert, J. K. (2006) Deep-sea food bonanzas: early Cenozoic whale-fall communities resemble wood-fall rather than seep communities. Proсeedings of the Royal Soсiety B, 273, 2625 - 2631." type="journal article" year="2006">Kiel &amp; Goedert 2006</bibRefCitation>
). It was identified as 
<taxonomicName id="D7F84D4FFFB4FFF6FC572F68FB95FCB5" authorityName="Gray" authorityYear="1847" box="[1012,1146,847,872]" class="Polyplacophora" family="Leptochitonidae" genus="Leptochiton" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neoloricata" pageId="2" pageNumber="303" phylum="Mollusca" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="228CEADEFFB4FFF6FC572F68FB95FCB5" box="[1012,1146,847,872]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="303">Leptochiton</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
sp. After my own careful examination of this valve (
<collectionCode id="76E9AE09FFB4FFF6FE622F53FDFBFC51" box="[449,532,884,908]" country="USA" httpUri="http://biocol.org/urn:lsid:biocol.org:col:34871" name="Smithsonian Institution, National Museum of Natural History" pageId="2" pageNumber="303">USNM</collectionCode>
531405), I believe it belongs to 
<taxonomicName id="D7F84D4FFFB4FFF6FC232F53FBE5FC50" authorityName="Sirenko" authorityYear="1988" box="[896,1034,884,909]" class="Polyplacophora" family="Leptochitonidae" genus="Ferreiraella" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidopleurida" pageId="2" pageNumber="303" phylum="Mollusca" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="228CEADEFFB4FFF6FC232F53FBE5FC50" box="[896,1034,884,909]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="303">Ferreiraella</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
because it is rather wide and has an arrangement of aesthete pores that is very typical for the genus 
<taxonomicName id="D7F84D4FFFB4FFF6FC0B2FB0FBDEFC6D" authorityName="Sirenko" authorityYear="1988" box="[936,1073,919,944]" class="Polyplacophora" family="Leptochitonidae" genus="Ferreiraella" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidopleurida" pageId="2" pageNumber="303" phylum="Mollusca" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="228CEADEFFB4FFF6FC0B2FB0FBDEFC6D" box="[936,1073,919,944]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="303">Ferreiraella</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Judging from the disjunctive distribution of the deep water inhabiting ferreiraellids, their origin may be from the end of the Paleozoic (
<bibRefCitation id="74694B3DFFB4FFF6FAE02F9BFF3CFC25" author="Sirenko" pageId="2" pageNumber="303" refId="ref16854" refString="Sirenko, V. I. (1988) A new genus of deep sea chitons Ferreiraella gen. n. (Lepidopleurida, Leptochitonidae) with a description of a new ultra-abyssal species. Zoologiсal Journal, 67 (12), 1776 - 1786." type="journal article" year="1988">Sirenko 1988</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
